# Summary :
Dropping zero-variance reduces the number of features required to train the model. This is particularly significant when dealing with datasets with a large number of features.

There are other ways to deal with non-zero low variant features like PCA, but that's a topic for another day.

source.9774b06f:
Looking at the plots can see that feature 'INDUS' is distributed over a wide range, Feature "F1" does not vary at all and outputs a constant value, Feature "F3" varies, but the amount of variation is not very significant. This visualization was great since we had only few features on our dataset, but what if our dataset has 200+ features. In that case we can find the non-variant features by sklearns VarianceThreshold in feature_selection library. 📘

The VarianveThreshold takes a parameter 'threshold' which can be set by the user to detect features below certain variance. For e.g setting variance to 0(default) will detect features which have zero or no variance, setting it to 10 to detect features below that variance amount

In the first case lets try with variance zero, we will then call the fit method usually done on training data and spot the redundant columns.

# Description :
Often time when dealing with a dataset with a large number of features, it is common to observe features that have very low variance(mostly zero). It is easy to spot those as they would typically have a constant value, or their value change so little that it supplies no useful information for our model to learn weights.

It is a good practice to drop these redundant features, enabling our model to train faster and achieve better performance. In this article, I will demonstrate how to spot features with a low variance that can be avoided to train your model.

In the end, I will also list some other techniques that could be used to tackle the low variance problem.
